&lt;div class=&quot;content-intro&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why DH Pace?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The DH Pace Company is a family-owned and privately held business with annual sales over $1 billion through 60+ offices located across the continental United States. The Company is an industry leader in the distribution, installation, maintenance, and repair of a complete range of commercial, industrial, and residential door, docking and security products. In 2026, DH Pace is celebrating its 100&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; anniversary in business.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DH Pace Company, Inc.&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;nbsp;aspires to hire an &lt;strong&gt;Area&amp;nbsp;Materials Manager&lt;/strong&gt; at our &lt;strong&gt;Tempe, AZ&lt;/strong&gt; office. The Area Material Manager is responsible for the operational integrity of the materials management program across an assigned geographic area. This role carries broad accountability across procurement, inventory control, warehouse operations, receiving compliance, cycle counts, and the development and performance of materials management staff. The Area Material Manager is expected to actively manage vendor relationships, negotiate pricing, and drive procurement decisions that deliver the best value for DH Pace — while serving as the area-level steward of inventory accuracy, process adherence, and materials governance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Job Responsibilities&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Lead and support the area materials management program, ensuring all warehouse and parts operations meet established performance standards for stock levels, accuracy, and operational efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Oversee inventory control across the full materials lifecycle — receiving, put-away, stock rotation, staging, and shipment — in alignment with company policy and the Materials Management Manual.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Drive cycle count programs and physical inventory audits for all locations within the area.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Monitor and respond to inventory reports including negative inventory, slow-moving stock, hot-list items, and shrinkage trends; escalate anomalies to Operations leadership.&lt;/li&gt;
